<paragraph blockId="6.[137,776,214,706]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
Measurements.—Male 
<typeStatus box="[390,483,214,237]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">holotype</typeStatus>
with 
<quantity box="[550,661,214,237]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.214" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" unit="mm" value="12.14">12.14 mm</quantity>
CL; male 
<typeStatus box="[137,239,243,266]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">paratypes</typeStatus>
(
<emphasis box="[256,272,243,266]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">n</emphasis>
= 15), mean CL 
<quantity box="[468,581,243,266]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.214" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" unit="mm" value="12.14">12.14 mm</quantity>
; 
<typeStatus box="[592,684,243,266]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">paratype</typeStatus>
females (
<emphasis box="[146,162,272,295]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">n</emphasis>
= 10), mean 
<quantity box="[309,416,272,295]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.162" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" unit="mm" value="11.62">11.62 mm</quantity>
CL.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[137,776,214,706]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
PCW/FW mean ratio of male 
<typeStatus box="[496,598,302,325]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">paratypes</typeStatus>
(
<emphasis box="[616,632,302,325]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">n</emphasis>
= 15) 1.55, ranging from 1.73 to 2.09; female 
<typeStatus box="[542,644,331,354]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">paratypes</typeStatus>
(
<emphasis box="[665,681,331,354]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">n</emphasis>
= 10) PCW/FW mean ratio 1.99, ranging from 1.80 to 2.29, indicating that small-sized animals have a wide front and as they grow the front tends to narrow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[137,776,214,706]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
AL/AW ratio of male 
<typeStatus box="[407,509,448,471]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">paratypes</typeStatus>
(
<emphasis box="[527,543,448,471]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">n</emphasis>
= 15) 1.55, ranging from 1.38 to 1.89; AL/AW ratio of female 
<typeStatus box="[608,710,478,501]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">paratypes</typeStatus>
(
<emphasis box="[728,744,478,501]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">n</emphasis>
= 10) 1.41, ranging from 1.24 to 1.55.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[137,776,214,706]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
The mean total cephalothorax length of 
<typeStatus box="[590,692,536,559]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">paratypes</typeStatus>
of both sexes reached 
<quantity box="[296,409,566,589]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.193" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" unit="mm" value="11.93">11.93 mm</quantity>
, indicating a small-sized species. In four females carrying juveniles in the pleopods, the CL ranged from 
<quantity box="[275,481,624,647]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1179999999999999" metricValueMax="1.22" metricValueMin="1.016" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" unit="mm" value="11.18" valueMax="12.2" valueMin="10.16">10.16 to 12.20 mm</quantity>
. The smallest female found was 
<quantity box="[192,307,654,677]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.005" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" unit="mm" value="10.05">10.05 mm</quantity>
in CL and the largest female measured 
<quantity box="[137,245,683,706]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.458" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" unit="mm" value="14.58">14.58 mm</quantity>
CL.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="535" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[137,775,730,900]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
Distribution.—BRAZIL: State of Santa Catarina, Uruguay River basin, Canoas River and Caveiras River sub-basins. The tributaries of the Canoas River have high aeglid diversity in the same watercourse, as in lots UFRGS 3047 and 3950, where 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bond-Buckup and Buckup" authorityYear="1994" box="[281,402,847,870]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jarai">
<emphasis box="[281,402,847,870]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">Aegla jarai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[419,571,847,870]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
<emphasis box="[419,571,847,870]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. odebrechtii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos &amp; Bond-Buckup &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Finley &amp; Crandall" authorityYear="2012" box="[587,688,847,870]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oblata">
<emphasis box="[587,688,847,870]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. oblata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Santos &amp; Bond-Buckup &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Finley &amp; Crandall, 2012" authorityName="Santos &amp; Bond-Buckup &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Finley &amp; Crandall" authorityYear="2012" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leachi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. leachi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[208,266,876,899]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
occurred sympatrically.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="535" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[137,775,923,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
Etymology.—The specific epithet 
<emphasis box="[500,565,923,946]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">leachi</emphasis>
is given in honor of the eminent British zoologist Dr. W. E. Leach, who named the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1820" box="[245,306,982,1005]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[245,306,982,1005]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">Aegla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="535" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[137,775,1028,1198]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
Conservation status.—Vulnerable (VU) – B1ab(iii): Area of occupancy estimated to be less than 20000 km 
<superScript attach="left" box="[673,682,1053,1069]" fontSize="7" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">2</superScript>
; known to exist in fewer than ten locations; continuing decline, inferred from the quality of the habitat (
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN (International Union for Conservation of Nature)" box="[574,713,1116,1139]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" refId="ref8070" refString="IUCN (International Union for Conservation of Nature). 2001. IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria, Version 3.1. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland." type="book" volumeTitle="IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria, Version 3.1." year="2001">IUCN, 2001</bibRefCitation>
). The construction of a hydroelectric dam in this area is another threat for this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[137,366,1221,1244]" box="[137,366,1221,1244]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">Biology.—Unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[137,775,1268,1584]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
Remarks.— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos &amp; Bond-Buckup &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Finley &amp; Crandall" authorityYear="2012" box="[265,363,1268,1291]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leachi">
<emphasis box="[265,363,1268,1291]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. leachi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the group of the smallest species of aeglids, reaching a mean total LC that exceeds only those of 
<taxonomicName box="[279,396,1327,1350]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
<emphasis box="[279,396,1327,1350]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. muelleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[408,519,1327,1350]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
<emphasis box="[408,519,1327,1350]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. ligulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[531,649,1327,1350]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
<emphasis box="[531,649,1327,1350]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. violacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[661,768,1327,1350]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
<emphasis box="[661,768,1327,1350]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. obstipa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[137,230,1356,1379]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. prado</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buckup and Rossi" authorityYear="1977" box="[243,404,1356,1379]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leptodactyla">
<emphasis box="[243,404,1356,1379]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. leptodactyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[456,565,1356,1379]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
<emphasis box="[456,565,1356,1379]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. inermis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[137,775,1268,1584]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
The new species is distinguished from the other known species by the characteristic inner margin of the carpus of the chelipeds with modest spines, in number as in size and projection. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos &amp; Bond-Buckup &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Finley &amp; Crandall" authorityYear="2012" box="[262,361,1473,1496]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leachi">
<emphasis box="[262,361,1473,1496]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. leachi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares with 
<taxonomicName box="[507,621,1473,1496]" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">
<emphasis box="[507,621,1473,1496]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. inermis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the lack of a palmar crest, but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos &amp; Bond-Buckup &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Finley &amp; Crandall" authorityYear="2012" box="[333,432,1503,1526]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="535" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leachi">
<emphasis box="[333,432,1503,1526]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="535">A. leachi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by its more robust and globose cheliped, in addition to the different shape of the rostrum and the presence of a rostral carina.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
